 &amp;sup3; [Product Information]                                                     &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;                                                                           &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   Aspect-oriented programming (AOP) is a revolutionary new way to think   &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   about software engineering. AOP was introduced to address crosscutting  &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   concerns such as security, logging, persistence, debugging, tracing,    &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   distribution, performance monitoring, and exception handling in a more  &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   effective manner. Unlike conventional development techniques, which     &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   scatter the implementation of each concern into multiple classes,       &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   aspect-oriented programming localizes them.                             &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;                                                                           &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   Aspect-oriented software development (AOSD) uses this approach to       &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   create a better modularity for functional and nonfunctional             &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   requirements, platform specifics, and more, allowing you to build more  &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   understandable systems that are easier to configure and extend to meet  &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   the evolving needs of stakeholders.                                     &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;                                                                           &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   In this highly anticipated new book, Ivar Jacobson and Pan-Wei Ng       &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   demonstrate how to apply use cases?a mature and systematic approach to  &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   focusing on stakeholder concerns?and aspect-orientation in building     &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   robust and extensible systems. Throughout the book, the authors employ  &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   a single, real-world example of a hotel management information system   &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   to make the described theories and practices concrete and               &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   understandable.                                                         &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;                                                                           &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   The authors show how to identify, design, implement, test, and          &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   refactor use-case modules, as well as extend them. They also            &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   demonstrate how to design use-case modules with the Unified Modeling    &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   Language (UML)?emphasizing enhancements made in UML 2.0?and how to      &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   achieve use-case modularity using aspect technologies, notably          &amp;sup3; 
 &amp;sup3;   AspectJ.                                                                &amp;sup3; 
